post_text: Indiana Black Expo, Inc. has developed an extracurricular Performing Arts Academy open to students ages 13 through 18. The Performing Arts Academy (PAA) provides after school dance, music production, videography/photography, and acting programs to middle and high school youth in Central Indiana. The program components include weekly classes, academic support, and an infusion of Black History. Learn more by following the link!

Thank you to our teachers who collaborated to make these resources available for families. The Virtual Learning Resources page can be accessed though the Parent Portal, a link titled "Parents" in the top row of any district web page or by clicking below.

post_text:
Food Services is pleased to offer all virtual (grades K-12) and hybrid (grades 7-12) students the opportunity to purchase both breakfasts and lunches beginning on August 14, 2020.

3-Day meal packs for hybrid students and 5-day meal packs for virtual students can be picked up on Fridays at Lawrence Central High School, Lawrence North High School, and Fall Creek Valley Middle School between 11 AM - 1 PM. At the time of pick up, please bring your student's ID card. All students will have an ID issued to them from their home school this year. The amount charged to the student meal account will be based on eligibility for free, reduced, or paid meals.

Please visit the food services website for additional information.

post_text: This evening, football stadiums at Lawrence Central High School & Lawrence North High School will be illuminated between 10:14 PM and 10:22:46 PM in a salute to George Floyd, who was killed by Minneapolis police and whose death has spurred rallies across America. Mr. Floyd was born on October 14 (10:14). The MSD of Lawrence Township has a long and proud history of advocating for and living a culture of racial and social justice. Please note: Our campuses are still closed to the public as a result of the COVID-19 pandemic. Spectators will need to view the lights off school property. A drone will capture the event at both schools and this footage will be shared early next week.

post_text: Marion County Public Schools have united to stand in solidarity with our communities to build a more just and compassionate world, to abolish racism, value social justice, and respect human dignity. Marion County represents 11 districts and over 135,000 students. We support the Indiana Urban Schools Association Anti-Racism Statement and feel collectively compelled to state unequivocally that Black Lives Matter. We will speak out against institutional racism and express our unwavering commitment to eradicate it from our public spaces. We will learn, apply and teach anti-racism with urgency and intentionality within our school communities.

post_text: The 2020 recipients for the Becky Crum Memorial Lawrence Education Scholarship are Amea Givens from Lawrence Central High School, and Anai'ya Lee from Lawrence North High School. This $750 scholarship is given each year by the Lawrence Education Association to one recipient from each high school. The candidates are chosen from students who plan to pursue a career majoring in a social work, education, medicine, or other "helping" professions. Becky Crum was a veteran Lawrence Township educator and association leader who exhibited strength, a positive spirit and joy during her time on this earth. Congratulations to these two amazing young people!

May 7 at 4:30 PM ¬∑

Lawrence is a community that sticks together. We have seen that over and over again the last few weeks.

We need your help to make Lawrence an even better place to live. By filling out the 2020 Census, you will help us get funding for our city. Over $675 billion is allocated annually to state and local governments based on the census. This money supports education, housing, healthcare, transportation, and other services that are vital to Lawrence.

Make sure you are counted in the 2020 Census. Learn more about how you can complete the Census online, over the phone, or via mail at https://2020census.gov/en/ways-to-respond.html The Greater Lawrence Chamber MSD of Lawrence Township Lawrence Central High School Lawrence North High School

post_text: Be sure to check out The Leukemia & Lymphoma Society NEW Facebook Live Series: Hero Squad Live! beginning Tuesday, April 28th. Every Tuesday and Thursday at 2:00 EST, join Ms. Elizabeth from their staff for a fun and educational lesson straight from our K-8 STEM+ Curriculum, right on their LLS USA Facebook Page at https://www.facebook.com/LLSusa/. shared_text:
The Greater Lawrence Chamber
April 27 at 6:51 PM ¬∑

It was just announced that the Indiana Air National Guard will conduct an A-10 Flyover on this coming Thursday morning and Lawrence Indiana will get a couple of views of it. According to the flight path, the flyover will go from south to north on the western edge of Lawrence Township at 10:50am. Then the flyover will circle over Downtown Indianapolis and head straight over Fort Benjamin Harrison from southwest to northeast at 10:55am. Mark your calendars!

The Indiana Air National Guard 122nd Fighter Wing Blacksnakes will extend their salute to Indiana healthcare workers, first responders, military members and other essential personnel on the front lines of the fight against COVID-19. #WhyILoveLawrence

post_text: Rose-Hulman's AskRose Homework Help has added daytime hours to help homebound students better understand math and science homework problems from their virtual or online courses during this public health crisis. Help is available Monday through Friday between noon and 3 PM (Eastern) by phone, email or chat. Traditional hours are unchanged: Sunday through Thursday 7 PM - 10 PM (Eastern). Students may call 1-877-ASK-ROSE (1-877-275-7673) or email/chat on the AskRose website, AskRose.org. The site offers more than 500 resources through videos and downloadable reference materials.

post_text: PRINTED MATERIALS UPDATE*** As we navigate this unexpected, extended closure, there are bound to be scenarios that arise and force us to adjust our plans. This morning, we learned that our current vendor was unable to secure the copies needed to provide packets for five days of instruction. These packets were scheduled for pick up today. With this change, only two days of instructional materials will be available for pick up today. We are working with the vendor, and have been assured that the remaining materials will be available this week. Parents can pick up these packets at their child‚Äôs school on Thursday, March 19th between 11 AM ‚Äì 1 PM. Lessons for the week of March 23 will be available on the 23rd between 10 AM ‚Äì 3 PM, as originally scheduled. Please keep in mind that all lessons are currently available to the public online at ltschools.org/extended-closure-resources. We apologize for the inconvenience and appreciate your patience.
